# Python Coding Conventions

## Context
- Applies to all Python files in the project
- Ensures consistent code style across the codebase
- Leverages Python 3.13+ features

## Requirements
- Use Python 3.13+ features and type hints extensively
- Follow PEP 8 with 120 character line length limit
- Use double quotes for strings consistently
- All functions and methods must have docstrings
- Prefer built-in types (dict[str, Any] over Dict[str, Any])
- Use | for union types instead of Union (e.g., str | None)
- Group imports: standard library, third-party, local (separated by blank lines)
- Use absolute imports for app modules
- One import per line

## Examples
<example>
# Good: Proper type hints and docstring
async def get_user(user_id: UUID) -> User | None:
    """
    Retrieve a user by their ID.
    
    Args:
        user_id: The UUID of the user to retrieve
        
    Returns:
        User object if found, None otherwise
    """
    async with get_session() as session:
        return await session.get(User, user_id)
</example>

<example type="invalid">
# Invalid: Missing type hints and using old-style Union
from typing import Union

def get_user(user_id):
    # No docstring
    return session.get(User, user_id)
</example>